dict.string: This category includes content that is considered safe and generally required for Internet functionality overall.

Facebook is a social network which allows users to create profiles, post messages and media to their own or others' profiles, and interact through liking and comments. It is available through a number of different venues, such as their website, Facebook Apps, and their alternative app called Paper.

YouTube is a video streaming platform in which users can submit and share content publicly for viewers to consume. Content is diverse, but some is of an adult nature. Some tools are in place to help users avoid mature or explicit content if desired, but these are difficult to enforce. The kids' app "YouTube Kids" is a recommended avenue for allowing younger kids to view video on YouTube.

Instagram is a photo and video sharing social app. Users can post, view, and share photos and videos across a variety of social networks. Users must be 13 years old or older. Instagram works to keep explicit content out of its service, but mature content is still available.

Netflix is a subscription-based movie and TV streaming service. Parental controls are available (though easily circumvented), and they must be closely managed by parents to be useful. Netflix use can also be very data-heavy, so communication regarding Netflix on the go is recommended.

Pinterest is a social curation platform in which users can create collections--called 'boards'--of images and other media around topics of interest. These can be kept private or made public for others to view. While sexually-explicit content is restricted on Pinterest, there is a wealth of other mature content that many would deem unsuitable for kids or teens.

Snapchat is a video and photo sharing platform in which media that is shared expires after a short period of time. This is a very popular app, especially among younger users, though the expiration of content is not as guaranteed as the app marketing would suggest. Many use Snapchat as a primary way to stay connected with friends, though some use it to share inappropriate or explicit content.
Tumblr is a blogging platform where users post content they want to their personal blog. The content is very diverse, though much is adult. Tumblr does not actively flag or filter explicit content.

Minecraft is a first-person video game in which players explore an open sandbox world, gather resources, and create, both in survival and creative modes. Survival mode could be scary for younger players, despite the relatively simple graphics that the game employs, given that the player may be attacked by spiders, zombies, and more.

Nickelodeon is an established media company that creates content primarily for kids. While much of the content is appropriate for all ages, some content is better suited for tweens and teens than younger kids.
Cartoon Network app has cartoons, full episodes, video clips and free games to play.
Club Penguin is a social game designed for kids to provide a safe and fun environment to play in.

Disney is a media and entertainment company with properties spanning animated feature films to online video and games to physical theme parks and consumer products. Much of Disney and Disney Junior content is appropriate for all ages, though because Disney serves a diverse audience, some content may not be suitable for younger kids.

PBS (or, Public Broadcasting Service) is a media non-profit providing a very large body of television, radio, and online content. Content available through PBS is very diverse and spans age-appropriateness. Parents will likely want to direct kids to PBS Kids where a number of kid-friendly shows may be viewed daily.

Periscope is a live video streaming platform. Users can brodcast as well as view video being broadcasted by another Periscope users. Live-streaming news events as they occur. Many others are mundane. However, some users on Periscope do use the platform to deliver inappropriate or even explcit content.

Meerkat is a platform that allows users either to view a live streaming video being broadcasted by another Meerkat user or to create their own for others to view. Some uses for Meerkat are very interesting, such as live-streaming news events as they occur. Many others are mundane. However, some users on Meerkat use the platform to deliver inappropriate or even explicit content, so discretion is advised.

Reddit is an online bulletin board that bills itself as the "Frontpage of the Internet" in which users submit topics of interest or comment on others. The wealth of content on Reddit is extremely diverse. Much of the content is relatively innocent and specific to particular interests, but some content is not appropriate for children and contains very mature or sexually-explicit content.
HBO Go and HBO Now are video streaming services that provide access to content from media giant HBO. HBO contains a mix of adult television content.

Twitter is a social media platform on which users can post or reply to posts at a 140-character limit called "tweets." While Twitter content is often unobjectionable, users can encounter adult content or experience cyber-bullying, depending on the people that a given user engages with on Twitter.

Amazon provides a host of streaming and content services, both on their site and through their Fire and Kindle products. Parental controls are available, but they must be closely managed by parents to be useful. Amazon streaming use can also be very data-heavy, so family discussion regarding Amazon on the go is recommended.
Hulu is a video streaming service that provides a wide-variety of entertainment. Access to some media is available only with a subscription.
FaceTime is a video calling and messaging app.

Musical.ly is a social platform for creating, sharing, and discovering music videos. While much of the content is unobjectionable, Musical.ly does not actively moderate the content on the platform, and it is possible to find songs or videos with suggestive, mature, or even explicit content.
EA sports hosts many popular online sports game titles, such as Madden NFL.
League of Legends is a free multiplayer online battle arena video game. The game is supported by micro-transactions.
Guild Wars 2 is a massively multiplayer online role-playing game.
Pandora is free personalized Internet radio with both free and subscription options.
Spotify is a music streaming service and app with access to millions of songs.
Kik is an app used for instant messaging. Like many other popular messaging apps, such as Facebook Messenger and Snapchat, Kik can be used to message individual friends as well as groups of friends.

Clash of Clans is a massive multiplayer online game which pits players against each other or a computer opponent. The app requires that players be 13 years old or older and features large-scale battles. It has in-app purchases.

Steam is a multi-player game platform and online store. It is used to distribute games and related media online. Steam provides the user with installation and automatic management of software across multiple computers, community features such as friends lists and groups and in-game voice and chat functionality.
Bungie games are popular multiplayer console games like the Halo series.
Khan Academy contains short educational videos with supplementary practice exercises and tools for educators. Everything on the website is available for free.
TocaTV is a kid's video streaming service that has a monthly subscription.
Vimeo is a video-sharing website and app that lets users upload, share and view videos. It contains both kid appropriate and explicit content.
Roblox offers kids millions of 3D worlds to explore, players to meet, and games to play in a family-friendly environment, freely accessible from any device anywhere.

Shazam is a mobile app that can identify music, movies, advertising, and television shows, based on a short sample played and using your device's microphone. It also provides a searchable music library where users can sample music and watch music videos.
YouNow is a live broadcasting platform where kids watch and stream real-time videos.
Houseparty is an app that allows up to eight smartphones to live stream video at the same time on the same screen and talk to each other.

Imgur is an image hosting and sharing site. Users can easily upload their own photos and share them with a simple link. Users can browse images with specific tags. This includes explict content, but it is filtered by default.

9gag is a user-generated collection of images, memes, and other media. While much of its content is relatively innocent, much else is labled NSFW (not safe for work) and contains mature and explicit content.
4Chan is an online bulletin board. Much of the content is mature and explicit.
GroupMe is a mobile group messaging app designed for ages 13 and up.
Contest of Champions is a free to play mobile fighting game featured Marvel characters. This app contains in-app purchases.
Flickr is a popular photo-sharing and hosting service. It supports a community where users share and explore each other's photos.
Xbox Live is a service for the Xbox gaming consoles for playing multiplayer games, watching TV shows, sporting events, and listening to music.
PlayStation Network is an online gaming service for the PlayStation gaming console. PlayStation Network allows for online gaming, watching TV shows, and playing music.
Tinder is a dating app designed for users 18+ years old.
Viber is a cross-platform instant messaging application for smartphones. You can make one to one video calls, send text messages, and send files to other users.
SoundCloud is a social sound platform where anyone can listen to or create sounds and share them with anyone.

WhatsApp is a cross-platform instant messaging application for smartphones. It uses the Internet to make one to one video calls, send text messages, and files to other users using standard cellular mobile numbers.
Skout is a mobile app designed for meeting new people. You must be 13 or older to use.
Game of War: Fire Age is a freemium mobile massive multiplayer online strategy video game that includes in-app purchases.
MeetMe is a online chat application that focuses on helping users discover new people to chat with on mobile devices.
Clash Royale is a mobile strategy video game that includes in-app purchases.
Mobile Strike is a mobile massively multiplayer online strategy video game that includes in-app purchases.
Bumble is a location-based social and dating app designed for users 18+ years old.
Badoo is a dating-focused, social networking service.
Omegle is a anonymous web only chatting and video chatting service.
Omlet Chat is a instant messagning application.

DeviantArt is an online community that allows users to upload original photos, comics, and drawings to their own profile. Users can comment on works of other users. The site does contain mature content.
Distractify is a website similar to Buzzfeed. Content on Distractify is mixed containing mostly adult content.
Upworthy is a video and ariticle website containing uplifting stories as well articles about lifestyle, and dating, and politics.
iHeart radio is a music and radio streaming platform. It let's users stream thousands of live radio stations and custom artist stations, as well as listen to music on demand.
BuzzFeed is a news site with, quizzes, videos, celeb news, tasty food videos, recipes, DIY hacks, and much more.

Trivia Crack is a mobile app that allows users to compete against friends and people around the world. The game's questions are based on 6 knowledge categories: Entertainment, Art, Sports, History, Science and Geography.
Ask.fm is a social network where users send each other questions, with the option of doing so anonymously.
ESPN's website and apps allow users to see various news and scores from a various amount of sports leagues. It also allows live tv viewing through a cable account.
LinkedIn is a social network that connects professionals of all kinds in the workforce. Users can update their professonial networks, create profiles, search / post jobs, and message each other.
Foursquare is a social media based app for public locations, like bars, restartaunts, etc. Users can leave ratings and build their profile by checking in when visting locations.
Yelp is a website / app that publishes crowd-sourced reviews about local businesses. Users can post their own reviews of buisnesses and serach for top rated local stores.
Super Mario Run is a mobile game featuring Mario from Nintendo. The player can try the game for free, and purchase the whole game via an in-app purchase.

Pok茅mon Go is a free-to-play, location-based augmented reality game. The game allows players to catch virtual Pokemon by walking around in the real world. Like most free-to-play games, this app contains in-app purchases.
Live.me is a social platform for broadcasting and watching live streaming videos. Users can host live video from their phones and get rewards from other viewers.
Flipp is a website / app that collects and displays fliers from local stores like Target, Ralphs, and Walmart.
Groupon allows users to sign up and recive discounts on various goods and services.
Timehop is an app that searches through your various social media accounts and compiles a list of what was posted exactly on that date a year ago.
Zoosk is a dating app that allows users to build and share their dating profiles with others. Like most, other dating apps, users can find potential dating partners and message each other.
This category includes sites that are dedicated to the purchase of apps, such as the Apple App Store and Google Play Store, or sites dedicated to downloading other software.

This category includes blogs that are hosted by major blog platforms, like Tumblr, Typepad, Blogger, and Wordpress, as well as personal sites with content curated primarily by the individual managing the site.
This category includes business-related sites across a variety of industries, including goods & services, finance, as well as sites related to employment, job postings, online meetings, etc.
This category includes sites dedicated to multimedia messaging services (MMS), online chat, bulletin boards, and forums. Circle does not manage SMS messaging.
The category includes sites related to artistic expression, in particular visual arts and movies, as well as dedicated venues like museums. Joke and humor sites are also included.
This category includes platforms dedicated to personal ads and dating, such as Match.com, OKCupid, or Tinder.
This category includes sites and apps related to learning, teaching, educational institutions, and career preparation.
This category includes web-based email providers.
This category includes sites that host adult content of an extreme or sexually-explicit nature.
This category includes sites related to family issues, such as parenting, adoption, etc.
This category includes sites related to online gambling, lotteries, casinos, and other gambling establishments.
This category includes sites dedicated to online game play. Note: Some sites that include games within a larger product (i.e., Facebook) will be categorized by that larger product鈥檚 features.
This category includes governmental sites, as well as those connected generally to politics, lobbying, activism, and military.
This category includes health-related sites, including personal health, medicine, and fitness, as well as sites related to sex education. This category also includes sites related to abortion.
This category includes sites for non-sports related recreational activities and interests, such as automobiles, model-building, and so forth.
This category includes sites related to family, home care, DIY, and food or drink (other than alcohol).
This category includes sites related to specific social issues, lifestyles, philosophies, and religion.
This category includes sites known to promote activities that are deemed malicious or illegal, including child pornography, phishing, botnets, and so forth.

This category includes sites that host content that is not sexually explicit but is still generally considered inappropriate for children or requires greater discretion. This includes content such as alcohol and tobacco consumption, as well as sites with an elevated level of violence or profanity, peer-to-peer services, or sites that may distribute content without the permission of the creators.
This category includes sites related both to musicians, as well as audio downloading or streaming.
This category includes news and news-related sites.
This category includes online storefronts and auction sites. This category also includes sites that sell intimate apparel and swimwear.
This category includes sites for photography related activities, as well as many sites displaying photos.
This category includes sites related to physical and social sciences, as well as technologies, like computers, AI, and so on.
This category includes all search engines and reference sites, including sites dedicated to translation services.
This category includes sites that host personal and professional social networking, such as Facebook, Pinterest, or Twitter.

This category includes sports-related sites, including professional teams, clubs, and sports media providers, as well as sites related to hobbies and recreation, such as automobiles or model-building.
This category includes sites that host and stream video on demand. Note: Circle does not filter specific content on these sites.

This category includes major known proxy and VPN providers, which are very similar. VPNs and proxies are technologies that provide security for online activity, protect user identity, and guard sensitive information related to their time online using the Internet. Because these technologies are employed to hide online activity, Circle will be unable to filter content while a user employs a VPN or proxy. This category is filtered by default for Pre-K, Kid, and Teen filter levels.
This category includes sites with content specifically geared toward a younger audience and may be considered appropriate for kids under 10.
This category includes sites related to travel and tourism.
This category includes content that is not yet categorized by Circle.
Turn on Ad Blocking to filter out many sources of online advertising and eliminate many ads from websites that you visit.

Turn on Safe Search to eliminate sexually explicit content from search results. Circle currently supports safe search for Google and Bing search engines. Searching with Yahoo will be unavailable while Safe Search is enabled.
Turn on YouTube Restricted Mode to activate the restricted content mode provided by YouTube.
